'''Bayard Dodge''' (1888–1972) was an Islamic scholar and president of the [[American University in Beirut]].  

==Background==

The son of [[Cleveland Hoadley Dodge]] and Grace Wainwright Parish, he graduated from [[Princeton University]] in 1909.<ref name=princeton />  

==Career==

In 1923 Dodge succeed his father-in-law, [[Howard Bliss]], to become the president of the university, that had formerly been known as "The Syrian Protestant College".<ref>{{cite news|title=Bayard Dodge Head of Beirut College|date=6 October 1922|work=The New York Times Company|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/06/99085574.pdf}}</ref> His great uncle, [[Reverend David Stuart Dodge]], had been one of the first professors to teach at the faculty in the 1860s.

After his retirement from the presidency in 1948 he continued teaching at several universities.<ref name=princeton>{{cite web|url=http://diglib.princeton.edu/ead/getEad?eadid=C0885&kw=|title=Bayard Dodge Collection of Photographs of the Middle East|publisher=Princeton University Library Manuscripts Division|access-date=30 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620180142/http://diglib.princeton.edu/ead/getEad?eadid=C0885&kw=|archive-date=20 June 2010|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His son, [[David S. Dodge]], later served the same role.<ref>{{cite news|work=The New York Times|date=21 July 1982|title=Lebanon and P.L.O join in search for American|last=Hijazi|first=Ihsan|page=8}}</ref>

==Works==

*''Aspects of the [[Fatimid]] Philosophy'', The Muslim World, L, No.3 (Jul, 1960)

*''[[Al-Azhar Mosque]]: A Millenium of Muslim Learning''. Washington, Middle East Institute (1961) - a comprehensive history of the world famous university mosque of Cairo.<ref>{{citation|editor1-last=Summerfield|editor1-first=Carol|editor2-last=Devine|editor2-first=Mary|editor3-last=Levi|editor3-first=Anthony|title=International Dictionary of University Histories|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6x3S8eM3spAC&printsec=frontcover|isbn=978-1-884964-23-7|page=13}}</ref>

*''The Fatimid Hierarchy and Exegesis'', The Muslim World, L, No.2 (Apr, 1960), pp.130-41

*''The Fatimid Legal Code'', ibid., L, No.1 (Jan 1960), pp.30-38

*''Al-Isma'iliyah and the Origin of the Fatimids'', ibid, XLIX, No.4 (Oct 1959), pp295-305

*''Muslim Education in Medieval Times'', Washington, Middle East Institute, 1962

