'''Denzil Doyle''' [[Order of Canada|C.M.]] is an [[electrical engineer]] and [[entrepreneur]] who has become a prominent figure in the [[Ottawa]] technology community having been the "founding president of [[Digital Equipment Corporation]]'s Canadian subsidiary, one of the region's early high tech leaders. He ran the company for 18 years, during which annual sales reached $160 million."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.obj.ca/Other/Archives/2005-08-31/article-2231620/Denzil-Doyle-named-to-Order-of-Canada/1 |title=Denzil Doyle named to Order of Canada |website=Ottawa Business Journal |date=31 August 2005 |accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref> In his role with DEC he is especially notable for having brought together Canadian nuclear scientists with American DEC personnel to create the computers that evolved into the highly successful [[PDP-8]] machines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca/eng/about/centennial/innovators.html |title=NRC’s Innovative People Profiles |website=www.nrc-cnrc.gc.ca |accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref> Doyle is the Founder and Chairman of Doyletech Corporation, has been its President since November 1982.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=141331&privcapId=23839137 |title=Executive Profile: Denzil J. Doyle |website=bloomberg.com |accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref> He is a Member of the [[Order of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gg.ca/honour.aspx?id=5328&t=12&ln=Doyle |website=The Governor General of Canada |accessdate=26 February 2017 |date=29 June 2005 |title=Denzil Doyle, C.M., B.Sc., D.Eng., F.E.I.C.}}</ref>
